Here is a clear review of the code, including bugs, security issues, and actionable improvements.

Issues in the code:

• Lost stack trace:
The timeout rejection uses a string ('timeout'). Rejecting with a string loses stack trace information and makes debugging difficult.

How to fix:
Reject with an Error object: reject(new Error('timeout')).

• Possible unhandled rejection from the original promise:
If the original promise rejects after the timeout has already fired, its rejection may become unhandled (depending on how the caller handles it).

How to fix:
Wrap the original promise to ensure its later resolution or rejection is absorbed. Example pattern below.

• Timeout remains active if the main promise resolves first:
The setTimeout is not cancelled when the main promise finishes, so the handler will run later, waste resources, or cause unexpected rejections if referenced improperly.

How to fix:
Use AbortController with newer APIs or clearTimeout. Example below.

• Cancellation not propagated:
If the promise supports cancellation (AbortController or custom cancellation), the timeout wrapper does not propagate it.

Possible improvement:
Add optional AbortSignal support.

Improved version with fixes:

function withTimeout(promise, ms) {
  let timer;
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    timer = setTimeout(() => reject(new Error('timeout')), ms);

    promise
      .then(value => {
        clearTimeout(timer);
        resolve(value);
      })
      .catch(err => {
        clearTimeout(timer);
        reject(err);
      });
  });
}

If you need AbortController support:

function withTimeout(promise, ms, signal) {
  let timer;

  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    if (signal && signal.aborted) {
      return reject(new Error('aborted'));
    }

    timer = setTimeout(() => reject(new Error('timeout')), ms);

    if (signal) {
      signal.addEventListener('abort', () => {
        clearTimeout(timer);
        reject(new Error('aborted'));
      });
    }

    promise
      .then(value => {
        clearTimeout(timer);
        resolve(value);
      })
      .catch(err => {
        clearTimeout(timer);
        reject(err);
      });
  });
}

Summary of improvements:

• Use Error objects instead of strings.  
• Clear the timeout to avoid unnecessary work.  
• Prevent unhandled rejections from the original promise.  
• Optionally support cancellation via AbortSignal.
